        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " having been mainly historical). Other alternatives arise from the structure of the heading. Like that in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 1:1-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is apparently composite. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:44-45",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 4:44-45",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " seem two independent titles; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:46-49",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 4:46-49",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " not only accumulate details after the manner of some other titles in the O.T. but contain a slight difference of style: in 47 D’s ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "towards the sunrising",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but in 49 P’s shorter form of the same (see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:41",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 4:41",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and the notes below). Other non-deuteronomic phrases are ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "set before",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "children of Israel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", thrice (see below on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:44",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 4:44",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); but both the contents, and with one exception the language, of 46–49 closely recall parts of chs. 2 and 3. Recently there has been a general disposition to break up the heading. Steuernagel supposes 44 and 45 to be respectively the titles of the two documents, in the Sg. and in the Pl. form of address, which he traces throughout chs. 5 ff.; Bertholet takes 44 as the transition from the first introductory address, 1–3, to the legislation proper, 12–26; and 45–49 as an introduction to ch. 5; Cullen takes 44 with 45",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "c",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as the title to the original environment of the Law code or ‘Torah,’ but 45",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ab",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "bc",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as that of the first combined edition of the ‘Miṣwah’ and ‘Torah’ (see Introd. § 1). The variety of these hypotheses alone shows their precariousness; and there is this further objection to finding in the double title, 44 and 45, headings to the original documents of D, viz. that even in these verses non-deuteronomic phrases occur. The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "whole",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " passage looks editorial: one piece (Dillmann) in the cumulative style beloved by later scribes rather than a growth from an original nucleus (Driver). Why then was it inserted just here? Dillm.’s and Driver’s answer, because at last with ch. 5 begins the actual exposition of the law, is hardly relevant; because in that case ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:44",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 4:44",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:45",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 4:45",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " would have contained some such verb as the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "expound",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " which we find in the title ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 1:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Indeed, that title is more suitable here than where it stands, for it describes better the expository and hortatory character of 5 ff. than the prevailing historical style of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 1:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—On a review of the data and these arguments it seems to the present writer more possible, and even probable, that part of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 1:1-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (and more particularly 5) originally formed the introduction to the combined discourses and laws, 5–26; that it was divorced from these by the prefixing to them of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 1:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and that when the whole book 1–26 was thus constituted, it was found convenient for its practical use to supply a new heading to chs. 5 ff. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 5:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " being too slight for the purpose), which should at once indicate that a new set of discourses begins here, and at the same time furnish a summary of the historical situation in which the discourses and legislation were delivered as described in chs. 2, 3. Such a suggestion is at least suitable to the salient features of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:45-49",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : that the language is partly post-deuteronomic and that part of the substance is based on chs. 2, 3.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 44.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "This is the Law",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - the Torah - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "which Moses set before the children of Israel.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"He meaneth that which hereafter followeth; so this belongeth to the next chapter, where the repetition of the laws begins\" (Ainsworth); cf. Deuteronomy ver. 1; 6:1; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. Deuteronomy 4:44",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Announcement of the Discourse upon the Law. - First of all, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:44",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", we have the general notice in the form of a heading: \"This is the Thorah which Moses set before the children of Israel;\" and then, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:45",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a fuller description of the Thorah according to its leading features, \"testimonies, statutes, and rights\" (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), together with a notice of the place and time at which Moses delivered this address. \"On their coming out of Egypt,\" i.e., not \"after they had come out,\" but during the march, before they had reached the goal of their journeyings, viz., (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") when they were still on the other side of the Jordan. \"In the valley,\" as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"In the land of Sihon,\" and therefore already upon ground which the Lord had given them for a possession. The importance of this possession as the first-fruit and pledge of the fulfilment of the further promises of God, led Moses to mention again, though briefly, the defeat of the two kings of the Amorites, together with the conquest of their land, just as he had done before in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:32-36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:1-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". On ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:48",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:12-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Sion, for Hermon (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]